  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "3224750c-f3ba-80a6-a37d-e66955d54901",
      "heading": "Summary Table PRED",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Moment of Prediction",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Quality of Next Interaction",
          "[0,1]",
          "1037 students in DB1\n180 students in DB2\n52 students in DB3",
          "DB1 - 5 Courses in FMH\n\nDB2 - 1 Course in a UAE university\n\nDB3 - 1 Course in a Greek University ",
          "LMS logs",
          "[C1 to C14]",
          "",
          "The interesting thing about this work is that it uses 3 different databases at different resolutions:\n\nInstitutional, \nCourse and Discipline. \n\nThe raw logs are given to a categorization module that extracts 14 features and these are subsequently fed into a Quality of Interaction Module that converts the logs into a quality of interaction score. The output of the quality of interactions is subsequently fed to an LSTM, which then predicts QoI for next interaction.\n",
          "DeepLMS\nFCM-QoI",
          "Holdout Method",
          "DB1\n{RMSE: 0.0086 - DeepLMS, Spearman Correlation: 0.98 - DeepLMS}\n\nDB2\n{RMSE: 0.0043 - DeepLMS, Spearman Correlation: 0.96 - DeepLMS}\n\nDB3\n{RMSE: 0.0039 - DeepLMS, Spearman Correlation: 0.99 - DeepLMS}",
          "DeepLMS is a deep learning system designed to predict how well a user is engaging with an online learning platform (LMS), specifically Moodle. The motivation comes from the Covid-19 pandemic, which forced a sudden shift to online learning and created a need for tools that could monitor and support that process in real time.\nThe system works in two stages. First, a pre-existing fuzzy logic model called FuzzyQoI takes raw LMS interaction logs — things like login frequency, resource access, forum activity — and converts them into a single daily quality of interaction (QoI) score per user, normalized between 0 and 1. Second, an LSTM neural network is trained on each user's historical QoI scores to predict their next day's score.\nThe practical output is a feedback signal. By comparing the current QoI with the predicted next QoI, the system generates a difference score that can trigger personalized alerts — warning a student or educator when engagement is expected to drop, before it actually does.\nThe model was tested on data from three universities across Portugal, UAE and Greece, covering both pre- and during-Covid periods, and involving over 1,300 users and 647,000 LMS interactions in total. Across all three datasets the model achieved very low prediction error and high correlation with actual QoI values, and performed considerably better than the previous benchmark model.\nThe authors are careful to position QoI prediction as a complement to traditional grading, not a replacement, and acknowledge that whether QoI actually correlates with academic outcomes remains an open question for future work.",
          "No prediction of grade/performance\n\nNo correlation analysis was done between QoI and actual academic performance (grades, exams) \n\nData covers only one or half an academic year per database, limiting confidence in long-term consistency.\n\nThe feedback mechanism is proposed conceptually but never actually tested with real users to see if it changes behavior.\n\nDB2 has only 76 days total, meaning the test window is around 8 days — very thin for drawing strong conclusions.\n\nThe model is trained and tested on the same users across time, so true generalization to new, unseen individuals is never demonstrated.\n\nThe three databases differ substantially in size, duration and scale, making direct cross-database comparisons difficult to interpret cleanly.\n\n\n\n\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
